Date: Mon 24 Apr 2006
From: Christian Griot <Christian.Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: AP and Cattlenetwork.com, 24 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://www.cattlenetwork.com/content.asp?contentid=31551>

Mongolian suburb under quarantine after foot and mouth found
------------------------------------------------------------
A suburb on the outskirts of the Mongolian capital of Ulaanbaatar has been
quarantined after health officials confirmed that a sick cow died of foot
and mouth disease [FMD].
The Mongolian General Authority for Emergency Management said Sunday [23
Apr 2006] that the cow in Zaisan died on 22 Apr 2006 of foot and mouth
disease. Some 430 livestock and 98 people [see comment] in the area have
been put under quarantine, the agency said on national television. No other
details were given.
FMD affects cows, sheep, goats and other cloven-footed animals, causing
blisters on the mouth and feet. It isn't usually fatal, but authorities
usually slaughter animals to stop its spread, because outbreaks often
prompt governments to ban meat imports from the affected country.
While Mongolia doesn't export meat, the disease can have a big impact on
the impoverished former Soviet satellite, where many people are traditional
nomadic herders of cattle and sheep.
--
Christian Griot
<Christian.Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
[While FMD may cause considerable mortality, mainly in young animals, its
economic impact might also be very significant due to its rapid spread, its
impact upon the productivity of farm animals (mainly ruminants and swine),
its debilitating effect, and extended convalescence period. It is likely
that additional cases will be seen among the quarantined in-contact
animals; a single case in an adult (vaccinated?) animal is unusual.
FMD is not regarded as a zoonotic disease; the movement restrictions on
people mentioned above have most probably been applied by the Mongolian
authorities to prevent the possible mechanical spread of the virus. It is
not clear why pregnant women are being examined in relation to FMD, perhaps
because of an extremely precautionary attitude?!
The previous FMD outbreak in Mongolia, in August 2005, was caused by FMD
virus serotype Asia 1, probably of Chinese origin. An official lab
confirmation of the current causative agent, followed by a notification of
the outbreak to the OIE, are anticipated. - Mod.AS]
